{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17776"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17776"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.95,0.02,0.03,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10490"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57844"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6555"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24519"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with acute sharp central chest pain that he describes as tearing and ripping. This pain radiates through to his back. He has a history of hypertension and is a smoker. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure is 180/100 mmHg, respiratory rate is 22/min, SpO2 is 96% on room air, and temperature is 36.7\u00b0C. There is a difference in blood pressure between his arms, with the right arm measuring 180/100 mmHg and the left arm 160/90 mmHg. Examination of his chest is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic dissection","Myocardial infarction","Pulmonary embolism","Pneumothorax","Pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of sudden onset sharp, tearing chest pain radiating to the back is highly suggestive of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E. The pain is often described as \u0027ripping\u0027 or \u0027tearing\u0027, and the presence of a blood pressure differential between the arms further supports this diagnosis. Aortic dissection is a medical emergency that requires immediate attention to prevent complications such as rupture or organ ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with chest pain that may radiate to the arm or jaw, but it is usually not described as tearing or ripping.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause sudden chest pain and dyspnoea, but the pain is usually pleuritic and not described as tearing. Additionally, there is no mention of risk factors such as recent surgery or immobilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E can cause sudden chest pain and respiratory distress, but the pain is typically pleuritic and not described as tearing. Examination findings such as decreased breath sounds on one side would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with sharp chest pain that is relieved by sitting forward, but it is not typically described as tearing or ripping. The pain is usually constant rather than sudden in onset.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aortic dissection typically presents with sudden onset of severe, tearing chest pain that radiates to the back.","The pain associated with aortic dissection is often described as \u0027ripping\u0027 or \u0027tearing\u0027 and is a medical emergency.","Prompt recognition and management of aortic dissection are crucial to prevent life-threatening complications."],"references":["Harris C, Croce B, Cao C. Type A aortic dissection. Ann Cardiothorac Surg. 2016 May;5(3):256. doi: 10.21037/acs.2016.05.04. PMID: 27386417; PMCID: PMC4893534.","Briggs B, Cline D. Diagnosing aortic dissection: A review of this elusive, lethal diagnosis. J Am Coll Emerg Physicians Open. 2024 Jul 8;5(4):e13225. doi: 10.1002/emp2.13225. PMID: 38983974; PMCID: PMC11231041.","Gawinecka J, Sch\u00f6nrath F, von Eckardstein A. Acute aortic dissection: pathogenesis, risk factors and diagnosis. Swiss Med Wkly. 2017 Aug 25;147:w14489. doi: 10.4414/smw.2017.14489. PMID: 28871571.","Levy D, Sharma S, Grigorova Y, Farci F, Le JK. Aortic Dissection. 2024 Oct 6. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722992."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57844"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17776"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57844"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T10:10:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T10:11:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10490"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72374"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"